<td style=3D"font-family:'Open Sans',Arial,sans-serif;"> <h2 style=3D"font-=
weight:400; font-size:24px; line-height:30px; padding:0; margin:0 0 15px 0;=
">Python</h2> <p style=3D"padding:0; margin:0 0 15px 0;"> The biggest news =
this year in Python is that creator and =E2=80=9Cbenevolent dictator for li=
fe=E2=80=9D <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/a0002W0vVF0F00OSEMQsSdr" target=3D"_blank"
>Guido van Rossum retired</a>, leaving Python in the hands of the <a style=
=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/R00WSFvMVr0000d2FFSsPQ0" target=3D"_blank"
>Python Steering Council</a>. So far, it=E2=80=99s been a painless shift in=
 power, which as Eric Matthes, author of <em><a style=3D"text-decoration:un=
derline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/m200QQ00S0VrvWdFMsG0FS0" target=3D"_blank"
>Python Crash Course</a></em>, argues, should come as no surprise, since =
=E2=80=9CGuido has carried himself, and his role in the community, with suc=
h poise for so long.=E2=80=9D 2020 will also see the <a style=3D"text-decor=
ation:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/qvSF0r2FWR0QSs00M0dH00V" target=3D"_blank"
>end of support for Python 2.7</a>, which will likely cause <a style=3D"tex=
t-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/b0000rMWsFI2SdvS000VFSQ" target=3D"_blank"
>its share of headaches</a> among holdouts. Meanwhile, Python continues to =
be the <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/ZMQSd0vTr0002V0FJ00WSFs" target=3D"_blank"
>language of choice for data science</a>.</p> <p style=3D"padding:0; margin=
:0 0 15px 0;">For Matthes, one exciting aspect of Python has been =E2=80=9C=
the variety of interesting and critical projects that [have] come out of a =
community where diversity has so intentionally been built for so long.=E2=
=80=9D <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/rS0K0S0s0MUWFQFvd02V0r0" target=3D"_blank"
>Carol Willing</a>, a member of the Python Steering Council and a core deve=
loper of CPython, also celebrates these projects=E2=80=94like the Binder se=
rvice, which promotes reproducible research by creating an executable envir=
onment from your Jupyter notebooks=E2=80=94particularly as they expand beyo=
nd their initial aims. Binder, she notes, =E2=80=9Cwas widely used [last] y=
ear for teaching workshops and tutorials at many Python conferences.=E2=80=
=9D Willing also offered a shout-out to the CircuitPython and Mu projects, =
asking, =E2=80=9CWho doesn=E2=80=99t love hardware, blinking LEDs, and sens=
ors and using Mu, a user-friendly editor that is fantastic for adults and k=
ids?=E2=80=9D </p> </td>=20
