<td style=3D"font-family:'Open Sans',Arial,sans-serif;"> <h2 style=3D"font-=
weight:400; font-size:24px; line-height:30px; padding:0; margin:0 0 15px 0;=
">Java</h2> <p style=3D"padding:0; margin:0 0 15px 0;"> It=E2=80=99s mostly=
 good news on the Java front. <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:=
#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/lsMVV000WvFd0S0rS0Q0L2F" target=3D"_blank"
>Java Champion Ben Evans</a> explains, =E2=80=9COnce again, rumours of Java=
=E2=80=99s demise have proved to be little more than wishful thinking on th=
e part of the platform=E2=80=99s detractors.=E2=80=9D But it hasn=E2=80=99t=
 all been smooth sailing. As we noted last year, <a style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/yvsFFVdQ0r0WSMM0SW00200" target=3D"_blank"
>the release of Java 11 in September 2018</a> brought a raft of new feature=
s, including many that give the release a significant, clear advantage for =
using containers. However, wide adoption of this latest release <a style=3D=
"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/Y0rSs0XQd00VF020WMF0NSv" target=3D"_blank"
>hasn=E2=80=99t followed suit</a>, with more than 80% of developers still o=
n Java 8, according to <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000=
;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/Y0rSs0YQd00VF020WMF0OSv" target=3D"_blank"
>this JetBrains survey</a>. Evans wonders, =E2=80=9CDoes this mean that peo=
ple aren=E2=80=99t running Java in containers as much as we=E2=80=99re told=
 they are? Or do people just not know about the benefits of 11 in container=
s?=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"padding:0; margin:0 0 15px 0;">Despite the slow=
 rate of adoption, Java=E2=80=99s <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; co=
lor:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/NM00PFVr002vdsS0ZQS0F0W" target=3D"_blank"
>six-month release cadence</a> has been trucking along=E2=80=94Java 12 drop=
ped in March 2019, with Java 13 following in September. And according to <a=
 style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/LVS0SM00v0Qs2F0Fd0W0r0Q" target=3D"_blank"
>Java Champion Trisha Gee</a>, it=E2=80=99s really starting to show its val=
ue.<br> </p>
<blockquote>
<em>Each release is quite small but predictable. And although they don=E2=
=80=99t all have exciting new language changes, you can see the language mo=
ving forward steadily. In addition, it enables this idea of preview feature=
s, which I think we saw working really well for switch expressions=E2=80=94=
developers got to try out the feature and give real feedback based on how i=
t feels to work with, instead of feedback on abstract, conceptual ideas. In=
 response, there was a small change to the syntax of switch expressions, wh=
ich was possible due to it being a preview feature and not set in stone, in=
 Java 13. Now this updated syntax is </em>
<em>scheduled to be part of JDK 14 as a production-ready feature=E2=80=8B.<=
br></em>
</blockquote> And 2019 brought another surprise when Oracle moved Java SE t=
o a subscription-based model. But as Marc Loy, coauthor of <a style=3D"text=
-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/JM0WFV0RvS0Q1sF0rd002S0" target=3D"_blank"
><em>Learning Java</em>, fifth edition</a> (now in early release), points o=
ut, =E2=80=9CThe Java community at large [has approached] this unfortunate =
change with <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/f00sr0W0FS02vM0VFQS2d0S" target=3D"_blank"
>increased enthusiasm for the OpenJDK</a>.=E2=80=9D<br><br>As for the comin=
g year, Evans suggests that 2020 will be about watching the trends that sta=
rted in 2019 play out.<br>=20
<blockquote>
<em>How close to a production version of <a style=3D"text-decoration:underl=
ine; color:#ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/E0r0F2d3MTF0Q0VS0s0SW0v" target=3D"_blank"
>Project Valhalla</a></em>
<em> will we be? Will the incremental strategy of delivering pattern matchi=
ng and algebraic data types (<a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#=
ee0000;" href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/c0S00VdF0WQM2vrS40FUs00" target=3D"_blank"
>Project Amber</a></em>
<em>) pay off? Will <a style=3D"text-decoration:underline; color:#ee0000;" =
href=3D
"http://link.oreilly.com/Q0sS0FM0FV0WV2Qvr005Sd0" target=3D"_blank"
>Quarkus</a></em>
<em> bear out its promise and the faith of its early fans? Will 2020 be the=
 year that Kotlin makes a significant beachhead beyond Android? These are e=
xciting times=E2=80=94we=E2=80=99re in transition towards something new and=
 there=E2=80=99s a lot going on.</em>
</blockquote> <p></p> </td>=20
</tr>=20
